pertly engineered tension control minimizes yarn breakage and produces a superior stitch. Lasts up to 60 years in a factory environment.','images/products/mg4d67-239x200.jpg'),(214,'MG-4D-45','M/MG Class','offm-mgclass',7,'showproduct.jsp?sel=offmgclass&code=9017',1,'4-thread, 1/8\" flat overlock stitch','images/products/mg4d45-145x121.jpg','The MG-4D-45 is designed for toe-closing on men?s and women?s hosiery. This machine is compatible with light to medium materials, creating a durable and comfortable finished product. Expertly engineered tension control minimizes yarn breakage and produces a superior stitch. Lasts up to 60 years in a factory environment.','images/products/mg4d45-239x200.jpg'),(215,'MG-3DW-7','M/MG Class','offm-mgclass',8,'showproduct.jsp?sel=offmgclass&code=9018',1,'3-thread, 3/16\" - 5/16\" flat overlock stitch','images/products/mg3dw7-145x121.jpg','The MG-3DW-7 is designed for edging medium to very heavy knits and wovens with a 1/4\" three-thread overedge stitch.','images/products/mg3dw7-239x200.jpg'),(216,'High Arm Crochet Class','Machines','offmachines',1,'view.jsp?sel=offhigharmcrochetclass',0,'Crochet and crochet shell stitches','images/products/higharm-145x121.jpg','First patented in 1877, Merrow crochet machines remain the industry standard. A variety of crochet stitches gives you a range of effects for any fabric. Superior engineering means you get a perfect stitch every time, adding strength and decorative flair wherever it is applied.','images/products/higharm-239x200.jpg'),(217,'70 Class','Machines','offmachines',3,'view.jsp?sel=off70class',0,'Butted seams for all types of fabric','images/products/70class-145x121.jpg','Merrow?s 70-class machines produce unique butted seams for every fabric and application. With Merrow?s renowned engineering and the highest quality parts, 70-class machines are durable and reliable ? the perfect fit in any textile finishing plant.','images/products/70class-239x200.jpg'),(218,'M/MG Class','Machines','offmachines',4,'view.jsp?sel=offm-mgclass',0,'The original overedge sewing machines','images/products/mmg-145x121.jpg','Merrow?s versatile high-speed M and MG-class machines produce a variety of overedge stitches for applications from butt-seaming to decorative edging. Know throughout the industry as ?Merrowing?, overedge stitching creates a neat reinforced edge with decorative flair.','images/products/m-mgclass-239x200.jpg'),(219,'OEM','Products','(offproducts)',6,'soon.jsp',1,'Complete sewing solutions from Merrow\'s original equipment manufacturing partners.','images/products/oem-145x121.jpg',NULL,'images/products/oem-239x200.jpg'),(220,'The Overlock Stitch','Home','offhome',NULL,'view.jsp?sel=offoverlock',0,NULL,NULL,'<div style=\"margin-bottom: 10em\">An overlock stitch sews over the edge of one or two pieces of cloth for edging, hemming or seaming.  Usually an overlock sewing machine will cut the edges of the cloth as they are fed through (such machines are called ?sergers?), though some are made without cutters. The inclusion of automated cutters allows overlock machines to create finished seams easily and quickly. An overlock sewing machine differs from a lockstitch sewing machine in that it utilizes loopers fed by multiple thread cones rather than a bobbin.  Loopers serve to create thread loops that pass from the needle thread to the edges of the fabric so that the edges of the fabric are contained within the seam. \r\nOverlock sewing machines usually run at high speeds, from 1000 to 9000 rpm, and most are used in industrial setting for edging, hemming and seaming a variety of fabrics and products.  Overlock stitches are extremely versatile, as they can be used for decoration, reinforcement, or construction.</div>','images/products/parts-239x200.jpg'),(221,'Overlock History','The Overlock Stitch','offoverlock',1,'overlockhistory.jsp',1,NULL,NULL,'Overlock stitching, also known in the textile industry as ?Merrowing?, was pioneered by Merrow Machine Company in the late nineteenth century.  Joseph Merrow was the owner of a knitting mill established in Connecticut in 1838, who developed a number of technological advancements to be used in his mill?s operations. Merrow?s first patent was a machine for crochet stitching.  Merrow still produces crochet machines based on this original crochet model.  This crochet technology was a starting point for Merrow?s later development of the standard three-thread overlock machine, patented by Joseph Merrow in 1889.  Unlike standard lockstitching, which uses a bobbin, overlock sewing machines utilize loopers to create thread loops for the needle to pass through, in a manner similar to crocheting. Merrow?s original three-thread overedge sewing machine is the forerunner of contemporary overlocking machines.  Over time, the Merrow Machine Company pioneered the design of new machines to create a variety of overlock stitches, such as two- and four-thread overlock, the one-thread butted seam, and the cutterless emblem edger.  Today, The Merrow Sewing Machine Company is a leader in the production of industrial overlock sewing machines.',NULL),(222,'Types of Stitches','The Overlock Stitch','offoverlock',2,'overlocktypes.jsp',1,NULL,NULL,'Overlock stitches are classified in a number of ways.  The most basic classification is by the number of threads used in the stitch.  Industrial overlock machines are generally made in 1, 2, 3, 4, or 5 thread formations. Each of these formations has unique uses and benefits:  \r\n1-thread formations are used for end-to-end seaming, or ?butt-seaming?. \r\nTwo- and three-thread formations, also known as ?merrowing?, are the most common, used for edging and seaming, especially on knits and wovens.  \r\nFour-thread formations are called mock safety stitches and create extra strength while retaining flexibility.  \r\n5-thread formations, which utilize 2 needles, are called safety stitches, creating a very strong seam used for apparel manufacturing. \r\n\r\nIn addition to these classifications, Merrow often classifies its machines by their applications.  This is due to the sheer variety of Merrow machines and the stitches they create, many of which were designed for specific applications across a number of industries.  For example, Merrow has created machine designed for edging emblems, sewing netting, butt-seaming, purl stitching, and decorative edging.\r\n',NULL);
